## ✅ Index Creation Complete

### Pre-flight checks
| Check | Result |
|---|---|
| Table rows | ~500 million |
| Existing indexes | `orders_pkey` on `id` only |
| `user_id` index already exists? | ❌ No — safe to create |

### What was done
- Used **`CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY`** — the only safe method for a 500M-row table with 24/7 writes
- **No transaction block** — `CONCURRENTLY` cannot run inside `BEGIN/COMMIT`
- Lock acquired: **`ShareUpdateExclusiveLock`** (non-blocking — reads and writes continued uninterrupted throughout)
- Build time: ~180 seconds (expected; CONCURRENTLY is 2–3× slower but zero-impact on production)

### Post-creation verification
| Check | Result |
|---|---|
| Index `idx_orders_user_id` present | ✅ Confirmed |
| Index type | B-Tree |
| Active lock conflicts on `orders` | ✅ None |

### What was avoided
- ❌ `CREATE INDEX` without `CONCURRENTLY` — would have taken an `AccessExclusiveLock` for 10–30 minutes, freezing all writes
- ❌ Wrapping in a transaction block — would have caused `CONCURRENTLY` to fail
- ❌ Duplicate index creation — verified first

`user_id` queries on the `orders` table should now resolve in milliseconds instead of 10+ seconds.
